AttributeValuesData.AttributeValue: Flaky, grayish brown, divided by deep longitudinal fissures into rather long flat ridges. On old trunks rugged.

Swamp White Oak is a slow growing, long-lived tree that is now rare in Minnesota. In Minnesota, it is found most often in lowland forests on the floodplain of the Mississippi. Its shallow root system is particularly well adapted to survive regular spring flooding and the accompanying sedimentation. Most of its habitat was lost in the twentieth century when a series of eight locks and dams were completed on the river. The name bicolor refers to the leaf color: dark green above, silvery beneath.

Monoecious, appearing on the old or new growth. Staminate catkins pendent, clustered. Individual flowers comprising 4-7 lobed calyx which encloses 6 stamens. Pistillate flowers solitary or in few to many-flowered spikes from the axils of the new leaves.

Acorn. 3/4 to 1 1/2" long. Nut broadly ovoid, glossy, light brown, 1/3 enclosed within shallow cup covered by woolly scales, often with fringe of mossy hairs along cup rim. Often in pairs on 2-4" long stalk. Autumn; ripens in 1 year.

Alternate, simple, oblong-obovate to obovate, 3-7" long 1 1/4 to 4" wide, acute or rounded cuneate, coarsely sinuate-dentate with 6-10 pairs of coarse obtuse teeth, or sometimes lobed halfway to the midrib. Lustrous dark green above, whitish tomentose or grayish green and velvety beneath. Midrip yellowish, leathery in texture; petiole 1/2 to 3/4" long, yellowish
